</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy (HCM) is a heterogeneous group of diseases related to sarcomere gene mutations exhibiting heterogeneous phenotypes with an autosomal dominant mendelian pattern of inheritance. The disorder is characterized by diverse phenotypic expressions and variable natural progression, which may range from dyspnea and/or syncope to sudden cardiac death. It is found across all racial groups and is associated with left ventricular hypertrophy in the absence of another systemic or cardiac disease. The management of HCM is based on a thorough understanding of the underlying morphology, pathophysiology, and clinical course. Imaging findings of HCM mirror the variable expressivity and penetrance heterogeneity, with the added advantage of diagnosis even in cases where a specific mutation may not yet be found. The diagnostic information obtained from imaging varies depending on the specific stage of HCM-phenotype manifestation, including the prehypertrophic, hypertrophic, and later stages of adverse remodeling into the burned-out phase of overt heart failure. However, subtle or obvious, these imaging findings become critical components in diagnosis, management, and follow-up of HCM patients. Although diagnosis of HCM traditionally relies on clinical assessment and transthoracic echocardiography, recent studies have demonstrated increased utility of multidetector computed tomography (CT) and particularly cardiac magnetic resonance (MR) imaging in diagnosis, phenotype differentiation, therapeutic planning, and prognostication. In this article, we provide an overview of the genetics, pathophysiology, and clinical manifestations of HCM, with the spectrum of imaging findings at MR imaging and CT and their contribution in diagnosis, risk stratification, and therapy.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2016</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2016150137">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2016150137">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig1a.jpeg" height="747" width="737" aria-labelledby="fig1a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span>. Variable expressivity and penetrance of <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr>. <b>(a, b)</b> Diastolic <b>(a)</b> and systolic <b>(b)</b> four-chamber steady-state free-precession (<abbr title="steady-state free-precession">SSFP</abbr>) cine MR images in a 16-year-old boy with a family history of <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> undergoing screening with MR imaging show <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr>-phenotype-positive severe septal hypertrophy (arrow), near obliteration of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> chamber with an ejection fraction of 78% (arrowhead), and moderate mitral valve regurgitation and systolic anterior motion of the mitral valve leaflets (<abbr title="systolic anterior motion of the mitral valve leaflets">SAM</abbr>) (not shown). <b>(c, d)</b> Diastolic <b>(c)</b> and systolic <b>(d)</b> four-chamber <abbr title="steady-state free-precession">SSFP</abbr> cine MR images in a 15-year-old girl with a family history of <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> who presented with palpitations show no phenotypic morphology of <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> (<abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> phenotype negative) and no mitral regurgitation or <abbr title="systolic anterior motion of the mitral valve leaflets">SAM</abbr> (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig1a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig1b.jpeg" height="747" width="738" aria-labelledby="fig1b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span>. Variable expressivity and penetrance of <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr>. <b>(a, b)</b> Diastolic <b>(a)</b> and systolic <b>(b)</b> four-chamber steady-state free-precession (<abbr title="steady-state free-precession">SSFP</abbr>) cine MR images in a 16-year-old boy with a family history of <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> undergoing screening with MR imaging show <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr>-phenotype-positive severe septal hypertrophy (arrow), near obliteration of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> chamber with an ejection fraction of 78% (arrowhead), and moderate mitral valve regurgitation and systolic anterior motion of the mitral valve leaflets (<abbr title="systolic anterior motion of the mitral valve leaflets">SAM</abbr>) (not shown). <b>(c, d)</b> Diastolic <b>(c)</b> and systolic <b>(d)</b> four-chamber <abbr title="steady-state free-precession">SSFP</abbr> cine MR images in a 15-year-old girl with a family history of <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> who presented with palpitations show no phenotypic morphology of <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> (<abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> phenotype negative) and no mitral regurgitation or <abbr title="systolic anterior motion of the mitral valve leaflets">SAM</abbr> (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig1b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig1c.jpeg" height="735" width="735" aria-labelledby="fig1c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1c</span>. Variable expressivity and penetrance of <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr>. <b>(a, b)</b> Diastolic <b>(a)</b> and systolic <b>(b)</b> four-chamber steady-state free-precession (<abbr title="steady-state free-precession">SSFP</abbr>) cine MR images in a 16-year-old boy with a family history of <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> undergoing screening with MR imaging show <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr>-phenotype-positive severe septal hypertrophy (arrow), near obliteration of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> chamber with an ejection fraction of 78% (arrowhead), and moderate mitral valve regurgitation and systolic anterior motion of the mitral valve leaflets (<abbr title="systolic anterior motion of the mitral valve leaflets">SAM</abbr>) (not shown). <b>(c, d)</b> Diastolic <b>(c)</b> and systolic <b>(d)</b> four-chamber <abbr title="steady-state free-precession">SSFP</abbr> cine MR images in a 15-year-old girl with a family history of <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> who presented with palpitations show no phenotypic morphology of <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> (<abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> phenotype negative) and no mitral regurgitation or <abbr title="systolic anterior motion of the mitral valve leaflets">SAM</abbr> (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig1c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig1d.jpeg" height="735" width="740" aria-labelledby="fig1d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1d</span>. Variable expressivity and penetrance of <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr>. <b>(a, b)</b> Diastolic <b>(a)</b> and systolic <b>(b)</b> four-chamber steady-state free-precession (<abbr title="steady-state free-precession">SSFP</abbr>) cine MR images in a 16-year-old boy with a family history of <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> undergoing screening with MR imaging show <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr>-phenotype-positive severe septal hypertrophy (arrow), near obliteration of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> chamber with an ejection fraction of 78% (arrowhead), and moderate mitral valve regurgitation and systolic anterior motion of the mitral valve leaflets (<abbr title="systolic anterior motion of the mitral valve leaflets">SAM</abbr>) (not shown). <b>(c, d)</b> Diastolic <b>(c)</b> and systolic <b>(d)</b> four-chamber <abbr title="steady-state free-precession">SSFP</abbr> cine MR images in a 15-year-old girl with a family history of <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> who presented with palpitations show no phenotypic morphology of <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> (<abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> phenotype negative) and no mitral regurgitation or <abbr title="systolic anterior motion of the mitral valve leaflets">SAM</abbr> (not shown).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig1d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig2a.jpeg" height="771" width="640" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span>. Gross and microscopic anatomy of normal heart and heart with <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr>. <b>(a)</b> Gross four-chamber section view of a normal heart. <b>(b)</b> Gross four-chamber section view of a heart with <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> shows disproportionate ventricular septal hypertrophy involving the basal and midventricular regions. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph shows normal cardiac myocytes, as may be seen in a normal septum section (hematoxylin-eosin stain). <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph shows myocyte hypertrophy and disarray, as may be seen in an abnormal <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> septum (hematoxylin-eosin stain). (Fig 2 courtesy of William D. Edwards, MD, Mayo Clinic, Rochester, Minn.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig2b.jpeg" height="771" width="585" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span>. Gross and microscopic anatomy of normal heart and heart with <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr>. <b>(a)</b> Gross four-chamber section view of a normal heart. <b>(b)</b> Gross four-chamber section view of a heart with <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> shows disproportionate ventricular septal hypertrophy involving the basal and midventricular regions. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph shows normal cardiac myocytes, as may be seen in a normal septum section (hematoxylin-eosin stain). <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph shows myocyte hypertrophy and disarray, as may be seen in an abnormal <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> septum (hematoxylin-eosin stain). (Fig 2 courtesy of William D. Edwards, MD, Mayo Clinic, Rochester, Minn.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig2c.jpeg" height="701" width="933" aria-labelledby="fig2c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2c</span>. Gross and microscopic anatomy of normal heart and heart with <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr>. <b>(a)</b> Gross four-chamber section view of a normal heart. <b>(b)</b> Gross four-chamber section view of a heart with <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> shows disproportionate ventricular septal hypertrophy involving the basal and midventricular regions. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph shows normal cardiac myocytes, as may be seen in a normal septum section (hematoxylin-eosin stain). <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph shows myocyte hypertrophy and disarray, as may be seen in an abnormal <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> septum (hematoxylin-eosin stain). (Fig 2 courtesy of William D. Edwards, MD, Mayo Clinic, Rochester, Minn.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig2c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig2d.jpeg" height="701" width="941" aria-labelledby="fig2d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2d</span>. Gross and microscopic anatomy of normal heart and heart with <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr>. <b>(a)</b> Gross four-chamber section view of a normal heart. <b>(b)</b> Gross four-chamber section view of a heart with <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> shows disproportionate ventricular septal hypertrophy involving the basal and midventricular regions. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph shows normal cardiac myocytes, as may be seen in a normal septum section (hematoxylin-eosin stain). <b>(d)</b> Photomicrograph shows myocyte hypertrophy and disarray, as may be seen in an abnormal <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> septum (hematoxylin-eosin stain). (Fig 2 courtesy of William D. Edwards, MD, Mayo Clinic, Rochester, Minn.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig2d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig3.jpeg" height="1468" width="3800" aria-labelledby="fig3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span>. <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> phenotypes. Diagrams show normal or <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr>-phenotype-negative cardiac morphology <i>(A)</i>, focal basal septum <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> <i>(B)</i>, diffuse septum <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> <i>(C)</i>, concentric and diffuse <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> <i>(D)</i>, burned-out phase <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> <i>(E)</i>, midventricular <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> <i>(F)</i>, apical <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> <i>(G)</i>, focal midseptum <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> <i>(H)</i>, free-wall <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> <i>(I)</i>, and crypts in genotype-positive and phenotype-negative <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> <i>(J)</i>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig4.jpeg" height="750" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig4" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4</span>. Asymmetric septal <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> in a 43-year-old man. Four-chamber <abbr title="steady-state free-precession">SSFP</abbr> cine MR image shows asymmetric septal wall hypertrophy in systole (arrow). Also note the <abbr title="systolic anterior motion of the mitral valve leaflets">SAM</abbr> of the anterior mitral valve leaflet (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig4">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig5.jpeg" height="722" width="743" aria-labelledby="fig5" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figures 5</span>. Obstructive asymmetric septal <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> with an accessory papillary muscle in a 54-year-old woman. Four-chamber <abbr title="steady-state free-precession">SSFP</abbr> cine MR image shows asymmetric septal wall hypertrophy with an accessory papillary muscle attached to the basal septum (arrow). Also noted is <abbr title="LV outflow tract">LVOT</abbr> obstruction with a dephasing high-velocity jet seen in the subaortic region (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig5">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig6.jpeg" height="722" width="832" aria-labelledby="fig6" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figures 6</span>. Obstructive asymmetric septal <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> in a 62-year-old man. Four-chamber <abbr title="steady-state free-precession">SSFP</abbr> cine MR image shows asymmetric septal wall hypertrophy (arrow) and mitral regurgitation (arrowhead), seen as a linear dephasing jet into an enlarged left atrium.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig6">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig7a.jpeg" height="707" width="727" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Asymmetric septal <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> in a 48-year-old man. Short-axis two-chamber <b>(a)</b> and four-chamber <b>(b)</b> inversion-recovery images show patchy heterogeneous nodular areas of delayed enhancement in the thickened myocardium (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig7b.jpeg" height="707" width="847" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Asymmetric septal <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> in a 48-year-old man. Short-axis two-chamber <b>(a)</b> and four-chamber <b>(b)</b> inversion-recovery images show patchy heterogeneous nodular areas of delayed enhancement in the thickened myocardium (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig8.jpeg" height="650" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig8" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span>. Obstructive asymmetric septal <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr>. Three-chamber <abbr title="steady-state free-precession">SSFP</abbr> cine MR image shows asymmetric septal wall hypertrophy (arrow) and a narrowed <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> cavity with <abbr title="LV outflow tract">LVOT</abbr> obstruction due to septal hypertrophy. Note the high-velocity jet in the subaortic region (arrowhead). Maximum velocity at the subaortic level was 3.1 m/sec with a peak gradient of 38.4 mm Hg.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig8">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig9a.jpeg" height="642" width="782" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Concentric <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> in a 54-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Four-chamber cardiac-gated CT image shows diffuse and symmetric thickening (arrows) of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> wall. <b>(b)</b> Long-axis two-chamber <abbr title="steady-state free-precession">SSFP</abbr> cine MR image also shows symmetric <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> wall hypertrophy (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig9b.jpeg" height="643" width="793" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Concentric <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> in a 54-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Four-chamber cardiac-gated CT image shows diffuse and symmetric thickening (arrows) of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> wall. <b>(b)</b> Long-axis two-chamber <abbr title="steady-state free-precession">SSFP</abbr> cine MR image also shows symmetric <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> wall hypertrophy (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig10a.jpeg" height="742" width="825" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Apical <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> in a 59-year-old woman. Four-chamber <b>(a)</b> and vertical long-axis <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="steady-state free-precession">SSFP</abbr> cine MR images shows apical <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> wall thickening (arrows), resulting in a characteristic spade-like appearance of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> cavity. No delayed myocardial enhancement was seen at phase-sensitive inversion-recovery imaging.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig10b.jpeg" height="742" width="750" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Apical <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> in a 59-year-old woman. Four-chamber <b>(a)</b> and vertical long-axis <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="steady-state free-precession">SSFP</abbr> cine MR images shows apical <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> wall thickening (arrows), resulting in a characteristic spade-like appearance of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> cavity. No delayed myocardial enhancement was seen at phase-sensitive inversion-recovery imaging.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig11a.jpeg" height="823" width="763" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Apical <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> in a 39-year-old woman with increasing palpitations and syncope. <b>(a)</b> Four-chamber <abbr title="steady-state free-precession">SSFP</abbr> cine MR image shows the apical <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr>. <b>(b, c)</b> Four-chamber <b>(b)</b> and three-chamber <b>(c)</b> delayed enhancement images show patchy and nodular areas of delayed enhancement in the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> wall segments of maximum hypertrophy (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig11b.jpeg" height="823" width="812" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Apical <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> in a 39-year-old woman with increasing palpitations and syncope. <b>(a)</b> Four-chamber <abbr title="steady-state free-precession">SSFP</abbr> cine MR image shows the apical <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr>. <b>(b, c)</b> Four-chamber <b>(b)</b> and three-chamber <b>(c)</b> delayed enhancement images show patchy and nodular areas of delayed enhancement in the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> wall segments of maximum hypertrophy (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig11c.jpeg" height="730" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig11c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span>. Apical <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> in a 39-year-old woman with increasing palpitations and syncope. <b>(a)</b> Four-chamber <abbr title="steady-state free-precession">SSFP</abbr> cine MR image shows the apical <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr>. <b>(b, c)</b> Four-chamber <b>(b)</b> and three-chamber <b>(c)</b> delayed enhancement images show patchy and nodular areas of delayed enhancement in the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> wall segments of maximum hypertrophy (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig12a.jpeg" height="681" width="789" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Midventricular <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> in a 51-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Four-chamber <abbr title="steady-state free-precession">SSFP</abbr> cine MR image shows hypertrophy involving the middle third of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> (arrows) along with apical thinning, resulting in a characteristic hourglass or dumbbell-shaped appearance of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> cavity. <b>(b)</b> Four-chamber inversion-recovery image shows transmural apical enhancement (arrows). Also note the nonenhancing hypointense foci along the subendocardial surface in this region (arrowheads), compatible with thrombus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig12b.jpeg" height="681" width="785" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Midventricular <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> in a 51-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Four-chamber <abbr title="steady-state free-precession">SSFP</abbr> cine MR image shows hypertrophy involving the middle third of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> (arrows) along with apical thinning, resulting in a characteristic hourglass or dumbbell-shaped appearance of the <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> cavity. <b>(b)</b> Four-chamber inversion-recovery image shows transmural apical enhancement (arrows). Also note the nonenhancing hypointense foci along the subendocardial surface in this region (arrowheads), compatible with thrombus.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig13a.jpeg" height="640" width="761" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. Midventricular <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> in a 55-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Three-chamber <abbr title="steady-state free-precession">SSFP</abbr> cine MR image shows midventricular hypertrophy (arrows) and a focal thin-walled apical aneurysm (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Inversion-recovery image shows no delayed enhancement. The presence of an apical aneurysm increases the risk of thrombus formation and an adverse outcome.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig13b.jpeg" height="640" width="814" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. Midventricular <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> in a 55-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Three-chamber <abbr title="steady-state free-precession">SSFP</abbr> cine MR image shows midventricular hypertrophy (arrows) and a focal thin-walled apical aneurysm (arrowhead). <b>(b)</b> Inversion-recovery image shows no delayed enhancement. The presence of an apical aneurysm increases the risk of thrombus formation and an adverse outcome.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig14a.jpeg" height="668" width="793" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> involvement in a patient with diffuse symmetric <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr>. Four-chamber <b>(a)</b> and short-axis <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="steady-state free-precession">SSFP</abbr> cine MR images show diffuse thickening of the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> free wall (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig14b.jpeg" height="668" width="782" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> involvement in a patient with diffuse symmetric <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr>. Four-chamber <b>(a)</b> and short-axis <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="steady-state free-precession">SSFP</abbr> cine MR images show diffuse thickening of the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> free wall (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig15a.jpeg" height="753" width="826" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span>. Phenotype-negative <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> in a 66-year-old woman with chest pain. Cardiac-gated short-axis <b>(a)</b> and vertical long-axis <b>(b)</b> views show a contrast material–filled fissure-like invagination (crypt) at the inferior <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> insertion point (arrow). The crypt extends more than 50% of the myocardial thickness. There is no <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> wall thickening.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig15b.jpeg" height="753" width="749" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span>. Phenotype-negative <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> in a 66-year-old woman with chest pain. Cardiac-gated short-axis <b>(a)</b> and vertical long-axis <b>(b)</b> views show a contrast material–filled fissure-like invagination (crypt) at the inferior <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> insertion point (arrow). The crypt extends more than 50% of the myocardial thickness. There is no <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> wall thickening.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig16a.jpeg" height="889" width="666" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span>. Burned-out <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> in a 37-year-old woman with known exuberant <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> who presented with a new decrease in exercise tolerance, palpitations, and cardiac arrest. Parasternal long-axis four-chamber echocardiographic views in diastole <b>(a)</b> and systole <b>(b)</b> show exuberant <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> hypertrophy along the free wall, apex, and septum (arrows) with an <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> ejection fraction of 50%. Prior imaging documented a hyperdynamic <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr>, ejection fraction of 74%, and mild mitral valve regurgitation, which was now absent. The <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> ejection fraction continued to decrease and ventricular arrhythmias increased, prompting defibrillator implantation, which progressed to medically refractory heart failure requiring cardiac transplantation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig16b.jpeg" height="889" width="659" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span>. Burned-out <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> in a 37-year-old woman with known exuberant <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> who presented with a new decrease in exercise tolerance, palpitations, and cardiac arrest. Parasternal long-axis four-chamber echocardiographic views in diastole <b>(a)</b> and systole <b>(b)</b> show exuberant <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> hypertrophy along the free wall, apex, and septum (arrows) with an <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> ejection fraction of 50%. Prior imaging documented a hyperdynamic <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr>, ejection fraction of 74%, and mild mitral valve regurgitation, which was now absent. The <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> ejection fraction continued to decrease and ventricular arrhythmias increased, prompting defibrillator implantation, which progressed to medically refractory heart failure requiring cardiac transplantation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig17a.jpeg" height="740" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span>. Burned-out <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> in a 78-year-old man with long-standing asymmetric septal <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> who presented with increasing dyspnea on exertion and palpitations. An interval decrease in <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> ejection fraction from the mid-70s to 45% was noted, as well as mild congestive heart failure. <b>(a)</b> Cardiac MR image shows primarily <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> dilatation. Other findings were an <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> ejection fraction of 44%, septal maximum thickness of 18.5 mm at end diastole (previously 24 mm), and no <abbr title="systolic anterior motion of the mitral valve leaflets">SAM</abbr>. <b>(b)</b> Four-chamber inversion-recovery image shows subtle areas of scattered delayed enhancement, more prominent in the basal septum and anterior wall (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Coronary CT angiogram shows no significant atherosclerosis or stenosis, a normal aortic valve (arrow), and a nondilated aorta. Ventricular arrhythmia increased, requiring defibrillator implantation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig17b.jpeg" height="737" width="794" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span>. Burned-out <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> in a 78-year-old man with long-standing asymmetric septal <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> who presented with increasing dyspnea on exertion and palpitations. An interval decrease in <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> ejection fraction from the mid-70s to 45% was noted, as well as mild congestive heart failure. <b>(a)</b> Cardiac MR image shows primarily <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> dilatation. Other findings were an <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> ejection fraction of 44%, septal maximum thickness of 18.5 mm at end diastole (previously 24 mm), and no <abbr title="systolic anterior motion of the mitral valve leaflets">SAM</abbr>. <b>(b)</b> Four-chamber inversion-recovery image shows subtle areas of scattered delayed enhancement, more prominent in the basal septum and anterior wall (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Coronary CT angiogram shows no significant atherosclerosis or stenosis, a normal aortic valve (arrow), and a nondilated aorta. Ventricular arrhythmia increased, requiring defibrillator implantation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig17c.jpeg" height="738" width="781" aria-labelledby="fig17c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17c</span>. Burned-out <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> in a 78-year-old man with long-standing asymmetric septal <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> who presented with increasing dyspnea on exertion and palpitations. An interval decrease in <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> ejection fraction from the mid-70s to 45% was noted, as well as mild congestive heart failure. <b>(a)</b> Cardiac MR image shows primarily <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> dilatation. Other findings were an <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> ejection fraction of 44%, septal maximum thickness of 18.5 mm at end diastole (previously 24 mm), and no <abbr title="systolic anterior motion of the mitral valve leaflets">SAM</abbr>. <b>(b)</b> Four-chamber inversion-recovery image shows subtle areas of scattered delayed enhancement, more prominent in the basal septum and anterior wall (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Coronary CT angiogram shows no significant atherosclerosis or stenosis, a normal aortic valve (arrow), and a nondilated aorta. Ventricular arrhythmia increased, requiring defibrillator implantation.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig17c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig18a.jpeg" height="691" width="800" aria-labelledby="fig18a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span>. Diffuse <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> with an asymmetric septal component in a 35-year-old man who presented with palpitations and syncope. <b>(a, b)</b> Four-chamber <b>(a)</b> and short-axis <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="steady-state free-precession">SSFP</abbr> cine MR images show diffuse <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> hypertrophy, with a severe asymmetric component at the base of the septum measuring more than 5.0 cm in thickness (arrow in <b>a</b>). A gradient is present across the <abbr title="LV outflow tract">LVOT</abbr>, as implied by the dephasing jet seen (arrow in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Inversion-recovery image shows extensive fibrosis, characterized by foci of nodular midmyocardial delayed enhancement at the insertion sites of the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> as well as in the midseptum (arrows). The <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> ejection fraction was mildly decreased at 45%. This case highlights the role of cardiac MR imaging in risk stratification.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig18b.jpeg" height="721" width="804" aria-labelledby="fig18b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span>. Diffuse <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> with an asymmetric septal component in a 35-year-old man who presented with palpitations and syncope. <b>(a, b)</b> Four-chamber <b>(a)</b> and short-axis <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="steady-state free-precession">SSFP</abbr> cine MR images show diffuse <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> hypertrophy, with a severe asymmetric component at the base of the septum measuring more than 5.0 cm in thickness (arrow in <b>a</b>). A gradient is present across the <abbr title="LV outflow tract">LVOT</abbr>, as implied by the dephasing jet seen (arrow in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Inversion-recovery image shows extensive fibrosis, characterized by foci of nodular midmyocardial delayed enhancement at the insertion sites of the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> as well as in the midseptum (arrows). The <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> ejection fraction was mildly decreased at 45%. This case highlights the role of cardiac MR imaging in risk stratification.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig18c.jpeg" height="721" width="771" aria-labelledby="fig18c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18c</span>. Diffuse <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr> with an asymmetric septal component in a 35-year-old man who presented with palpitations and syncope. <b>(a, b)</b> Four-chamber <b>(a)</b> and short-axis <b>(b)</b> <abbr title="steady-state free-precession">SSFP</abbr> cine MR images show diffuse <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> hypertrophy, with a severe asymmetric component at the base of the septum measuring more than 5.0 cm in thickness (arrow in <b>a</b>). A gradient is present across the <abbr title="LV outflow tract">LVOT</abbr>, as implied by the dephasing jet seen (arrow in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Inversion-recovery image shows extensive fibrosis, characterized by foci of nodular midmyocardial delayed enhancement at the insertion sites of the <abbr title="right ventricle">RV</abbr> as well as in the midseptum (arrows). The <abbr title="left ventricle">LV</abbr> ejection fraction was mildly decreased at 45%. This case highlights the role of cardiac MR imaging in risk stratification.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig18c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig19a.jpeg" height="681" width="794" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span>. Postablation changes in a patient with obstructive <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr>. Four-chamber <b>(a)</b> and short-axis <b>(b)</b> inversion-recovery images show a large transmural focus of delayed myocardial enhancement involving the base of the interventricular septum (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2016150137/asset/images/large/rg.2016150137.fig19b.jpeg" height="681" width="781" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span>. Postablation changes in a patient with obstructive <abbr title="hypertrophic cardiomyopathy">HCM</abbr>. Four-chamber <b>(a)</b> and short-axis <b>(b)</b> inversion-recovery images show a large transmural focus of delayed myocardial enhancement involving the base of the interventricular septum (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2016150137&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Maron BJ, Gardin JM, Flack JM, Gidding SS, Kurosaki TT, Bild DE. Prevalence of hypertrophic cardiomyopathy in a general population of young adults: echocardiographic analysis of 4111 subjects in the CARDIA study. Coronary Artery Risk Development in (Young) Adults. <em>Circulation</em> 1995;92(4):785–789.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1161/01.CIR.92.4.785">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/7641357/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Prevalence+of+hypertrophic+cardiomyopathy+in+a+general+population+of+young+adults%3A+echocardiographic+analysis+of+4111+subjects+in+the+CARDIA+study.+Coronary+Artery+Risk+Development+in+%28Young%29+Adults&amp;author=BJ+Maron&amp;author=JM+Gardin&amp;author=JM+Flack&amp;author=SS+Gidding&amp;author=TT+Kurosaki&amp;author=DE+Bild&amp;publication_year=1995&amp;journal=Circulation&amp;pages=785-789&amp;doi=10.1161%2F01.CIR.92.4.785&amp;pmid=7641357">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="